Flight log has officially been enabled. I have 2.3 hours of flight records ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it feels like to drive a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a 4000-foot high motorcycle/off-road vehicle and a boat.
On the ground, the situation is constantly changing. The ground has a certain degree of instability, so you need a motorcycle/off-road vehicle.
By the way, you might not know that when you're driving a plane on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the steering wheel. You use the rudder pedals and the brakes. It's not like driving a car.
When flying in the air, you'll feel bumps and shakes, it's like sailing on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air flow will make you a bit dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to sailing.
By the way, here's another random anecdote：
Flying is very tiring. My back and legs are aching today, it feels like I went to the gym to exercise.
This is not as simple as taking a Sunday drive in a car. From my perspective as a newbie, it's more like a sport, not a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to the sky at 4000 feet.
Tomorrow I will fly again and we will practice stalling and slow flight.
Today's weather was not very stable, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalling. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 mph, while the airspeed was still 65 mph.
Today the weather is clear, and although there is a bit of fog at high altitude, the view is still great.
